LocationComment: Small park in Cambria's East Village. Zenith measurement taken 15 feet in front of Chinese Temple front steps.

SkyComment: Ten minutes prior to the start of astronomical twilight at 05:09. The sky looked very slightly hazy or milky. Perhaps some residual wildfire smoke was lingering in the atmosphere.  Cloud cover = 20%.  Transparency = Average.  Seeing = Good. Ursa Major & Ursa Minor partly obscured by clouds in the North, Polaris not visible. Orion and other constellations clearly visible. Lynx and Cancer at the Zenith.
LocationComment: Rural, rolling, grass-covered terrain north of San Simeon Creek Road and San Simeon State Park campground.Approximately 2.5 miles north of Cambria's West Village.

SkyComment: La noche fue estaba totalmente despejada, muy clara y sin viento. Había una ligera bruma en el ambiente debida a la humedad por la proximidad del mar que no impedía la visibilidad de los objetos, pero sí ayudaba a dispersar la luz de las farolas.    La Luna y Venus ya se habían puesto tras las montañas a la hora de la medida de oscuridad del cielo.    Las cúpulas lumínicas eran muy visibles hacia el Oeste (Adra), Norte (otras pedanías de Adra, Berja) y Este (Campo de Dalías, El Ejido, Roquetas de Mar, Almería...).     Las cercanas luces de Adra, muy deslumbrantes, impedían la adaptación completa a la oscuridad y su resplandor llegaba a superar el cénit. Había mezcla de luces de vapor de sodio a alta presión (anaranjadas) con otras claramente más blancas y azuladas (halógenas, LED). Muy mal apantalladas todas ellas (deslumbramiento, iluminación de la costa) y de intensidad excesiva (sobreiluminación).    Las luces de El Ejido llegaban al menos a 45º sobre el horizonte.     Eran apreciables diferencias de color en las cúpulas lumínicas de distintas poblaciones. Éstas afectaban mucho a la visión de la Vía Láctea. Únicamente se distinguía algo la zona de Sagitario. Sólo se pudo observar razonablemente bien bastante más avanzada la noche, cuando ganó suficiente altura sobre el horizonte.    Se notaba una gran diferencia al mirar hacia el horizonte Sur (mar), al no provenir luz del mismo.
LocationComment: Playa del Censo, al final del paseo marítimo de Adra, sobre la playa, justo delante del último espigón. Límite de la zona urbana.    El ayuntamiento apagó las luces de los últimos 500 metros del paseo para la actividad (observación con el alumnado y las familias del CEIP San Fernando, algo menos de unas 200 personas en total), con lo que la lectura y la observación fueron mejores de las habituales en ese lugar.     El alumnado participó en esta campaña de medida de oscuridad del cielo.

LocationComment: Hi! My name is Saujan Poudel and i am involved in amateur astronomy since i was thirteen. In my years long experience of observing, i  mostly observed from my house (The reported location) and never found any other location perfect for my observation. My house lies in a small village near densely populated market area, moderately light polluted area with a little sky glow. Even though my house is not free from light pollution in early evening but once it gets really dark and everybody is asleep, my house becomes a perfect dark sky site. Tall trees and houses helps to block light trespass from nearby dense area. My house area lacks the facility of streetlamps so, it is perfect for stargazing on a clear, dark and moonless night.

SkyComment: Sky was clear and steady from zenith down to an altitude of about 25°.  Below that, the sky was somewhat hazy and somewhat turbulent.  The haze enlarged the light domes from Madera (SW) and Fresno (SE) more than usual.  M82 (Cigar Galaxy), NGC 4631 (Whale Galaxy), and NGC 2392 (Eskimo Nebula) all showed mottling in an 11" SCT at 215x.
LocationComment: Central Valley Astronomers star party site.  Parking lot (1 acre) on east side of Eastman Lake above boat ramps.  Nearest lights are across the lake.  No trees within about 50 feet of site of SQM readings and those were <15 ft tall.

SkyComment: On this night, the sky was somewhat hazy, but cloudless. There was a faint glow produced by the sky and the stars, but not a clear contrast between the two. It was immediately clear that the stars appeared somewhat clouded and almost indistinctive from one another. While some major constellations and stars could be observed, it lacked the supporting detail of the stars that usually fill in the surrounding space. I could not observe the Milky Way.
LocationComment: For my light sky, I decided to observe the sky from farrand field. I had lived in Farrand my freshman year, and thought it would be neat to experience the night's sky in a familiar place, but with a new perspective. The area was well-lit and was clearly subject to light pollution.

SkyComment: The weather during the day was sunny and clear and extending into the night. There was a clear contrast between the dark sky and the bright stars, which created a dome-like viewing affect.
LocationComment: For my dark night, I observed the sky from an alley nearby my apartment building. While the observing location was significantly removed from any obviously light pollution, I would surmise that my chosen spot would be slightly affected by the neighboring lights.
